  [
    "Most millennials don&#8217;t save because their employers don&#8217;t let them",
    "MYTH BUSTING",
    "\n<p>Only a third of working millennials in the US are contributing to a retirement plan, according to a  <a href=\"https://www.nirsonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Millennials-Report-1.pdf\">new report</a> (pdf) from the National Institute of Retirement Security (NIRS).</p>\n<p>Without such savings, they face a difficult financial future in their 50s and 60s as few, if any, will be the beneficiaries of <a href=\"https://qz.com/679808/companies-with-defined-benefit-pension-plans/\">traditional pension plans</a>, which companies are phasing out. Payments from the government&rsquo;s Social Security program are likely to be delayed and reduced. In contrast, 51% of Generation Xers and baby boomers contribute to their own retirement plans.</p>\n<p>The poor participation of millennials in such plans isn&rsquo;t because they don&rsquo;t try to <a href=\"https://qz.com/1189328/millennials-believe-the-stereotypes-about-themselves-even-when-theyre-not-true/\">save</a> or invest. Many simply have jobs that don&rsquo;t offer retirement plans of any sort, or haven&rsquo;t worked long enough to qualify. Employers usually require new employees to stay with the organization for at least a year before allowing them into retirement plans. That should change, said Jennifer Brown, head of research at NIRS, because it&rsquo;s critical to save for retirement as early as possible to allow savings to compound.</p>\n<div class=\"inline-ad\" id=\"inline-1217392-1\"></div><p>&ldquo;If we fix some of these eligibility issues, we can raise the generation&rsquo;s participation rates,&rdquo; Brown said in an interview. &ldquo;When you see millennials move from job to job, they are usually moving to get better benefits.&rdquo; Individual employees under 50 years old can contribute up to $18,500 in tax-free earnings into company-sponsored 401K plans this year.</p>\n<p>Two-thirds of millennials do work for an employer that offers a retirement savings plan, but only 55% of that group are eligible to participate, NIRS found. Of that 55%, a whopping 94% do participate, the same as Generation Xers and boomers.  In 2014, more than half of millennials had spent a year or less with their current employers, according to NIRS.</p>\n<div class=\"atlas-chart\" data-id=\"S1OYl8m_M\" data-width=\"640\" data-height=\"449\"><img src=\"https://www.theatlas.com/i/atlas_S1OYl8m_M.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;\"></div>\n<p>Millennials are more likely to be employed part-time than workers of other generations, and part-time employees are less likely to qualify for job benefits.  Companies can require employees to work a certain number of days to qualify for a retirement plan, or offer different plans to different kinds of employees. The Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA) allows employers to <a href=\"https://www.dol.gov/agencies/ebsa/about-ebsa/our-activities/resource-center/faqs/retirement-plans-and-erisa-consumer\">limit benefits</a> to those who work at least 1,000 hours a year.</p>\n<div class=\"atlas-chart\" data-id=\"Sk741UmdM\" data-width=\"640\" data-height=\"449\"><img src=\"https://www.theatlas.com/i/atlas_Sk741UmdM.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;\"></div>\n",
    "Only a third of working millennials in the US are contributing to a retirement plan, according to a new report (pdf) from the National Institute&hellip;"
  ],
  [
    "The long lost painting known as Africa’s Mona Lisa has sold for a record price",
    "LOST, FOUND, SOLD",
    "\n<p><em>Tutu</em>, the iconic Nigerian portrait that was lost for decades, has sold for a record &pound;1,205,000 (about $1.68 million)&mdash;more than four times the highest estimate.</p>\n<p>The portrait of the Ife royal Princess Adetutu Ademiluyi, was missing for more than twenty years <a href=\"https://qz.com/1202249/lost-nigerian-painting-in-london-is-ben-enwonwus-tutu-portrait-for-bonhams-auction/\">until it was discovered</a> in a London flat last year. The painting is one of three depictions of the princess painted in 1973, which became a symbol of Nigerian reconciliation after the war for Biafran independence. Enwonwu is <a href=\"https://benenwonwufoundation.org/\">perhaps Nigeria&rsquo;s most renowned contemporary artist</a>, but his famous painting is believed to have disappeared from his studio in 1994.</p>\n<p>In a &ldquo;20-minute bidding frenzy&rdquo; the painting sold to a bidder on the telephone during Bonhams&rsquo; <a href=\"https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/24622/live/#/MR0_length=36&amp;w0=grid&amp;k0=59&amp;m0=0\">Africa Now auction</a> on Feb. 28, the London art dealer said in a statement. In the build-up to the auction, already optimistic auctioneers expected it to fetch as much as &pound;300,000. Instead, they set a record for Enwonwu&rsquo;s work.</p>\n<div class=\"inline-ad\" id=\"inline-1218563-1\"></div><p>For the first time, the auction was opened to bidders in Lagos, who took part in real time. The identity of the buyer was not provided. Another Enwonwu painting, <em>Negritude,</em> sold for &pound;100,000 (nearly $140,000) <a href=\"https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/24622/live/#/MR0_length=36&amp;w0=grid&amp;k0=59&amp;m0=0\">at the auction</a>, their sales <a href=\"https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/24622/live/#/MR0_length=36&amp;w0=grid&amp;k0=59&amp;m0=0\">overshadowing the other works</a> in the lot.</p>\n<figure id=\"image-1202282\" class=\"progressive-image inline-image  aligncenter zoomable size-small\"><picture style=\"padding-bottom: 148.14814814815%; background-image: url(https://qzprod.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/tutu_ben-enwonwu.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=50);\"><img src=\"https://qzprod.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/tutu_ben-enwonwu.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=50\" class=\"progressive-image-thumbnail\"><img data-srcset=\"https://qzprod.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/tutu_ben-enwonwu.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=320 320w, https://qzprod.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/tutu_ben-enwonwu.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=640 640w, https://qzprod.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/tutu_ben-enwonwu.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=940 940w, https://qzprod.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/tutu_ben-enwonwu.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1600 1600w, https://qzprod.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/tutu_ben-enwonwu.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=3200 3200w\" data-src=\"https://qzprod.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/tutu_ben-enwonwu.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=324\" sizes=\"320px\" class=\"progressive-image-large\" alt=\"Missing Ben Enwonwu Tutu portrait found in London flat will be sold in auction open to Nigerian collectors\"></picture><figcaption class=\"inline-image-caption\"><i class=\"icon-camera\"></i>A piece of Nigerian identity.<span class=\"inline-image-credit has-space\"> (Ben Enwonwu/Bonhams)</span></figcaption></figure><p>&ldquo;The portrait of <em>Tutu</em> is a national icon in Nigeria, and of huge cultural significance,&rdquo; said Giles Peppiatt, Bonham&rsquo;s director of modern African art. &ldquo;I am delighted that it generated so much interest and set a new world record for the artist.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>Booker Prize winning novelist Ben Okri described the painting as &ldquo;Africa&rsquo;s Mona Lisa.&rdquo; Even when no one had seen the real painting in years, posters Tutu hanged on the walls of homes around Nigeria.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;It amounts to the most significant discovery in contemporary African art in over fifty years. It is the only authentic Tutu, the equivalent of some rare archaeological find. It is a cause for celebration, a potentially transforming moment in the world of art,&rdquo; <a href=\"https://www.bonhams.com/press_release/25572/\">said</a> Okri.</p>\n<p><em><a href=\"https://qz.com/newsletters/africa-weekly-brief/\" target=\"_blank\">Sign up for the Quartz Africa Weekly Brief</a> &mdash; the most important and interesting news from across the continent, in your inbox.</em></p>\n",
    "Tutu, the iconic Nigerian portrait that was lost for decades, has sold for a record £1,205,000 (about $1.68 million)—more than four times the highest estimate.&hellip;"
  ]
]

